The CQB Comp, originally designed as part of the MK107 Rifle, provides as much compensation as possible while suppressing flash and sending all the blast forward of the shooter and those next to the shooter.
The CQB Comp features a 2 part design with a removable end cap for ease of cleaning. The primary function is to send all the blast forward while suppressing as much flash as possible.

title: For Sale:  REMINGTON RAND MODEL 1911A1  Late 1945 Production/Complete Rig C&R
postcontent: This is a great pistol for the collector of WWII handguns or 1911 pistols.it is a very late production Remington Rand that was manufactured close to the end of production in 1945. Completely original, this pistol has the correct light grey parkerized finish that was used in the last months of production (after about serial number 2,380,000). All parts are correct/original and the condition is very hard to beat, this pistol is nearly new! It has the correct late serrated slide lock, late 8-rib mainspring housing, HS contract barrel, correct hammer, correct Keyes Fibre grips, etc. The finish is completely original with the "P" proofs matching in size/shape and showing the characteristic burnishing, having been stamped after parkerizing. The ordnance crossed cannons, FJA inspectors marking, and the serial number also show the stamped after finish, burnished appearance. As expected, the bullet ramp is bright, milled after finish. The original light grey parkerized finish shows a few normal handling marks, but is one of those rare military 1911A1's that has almost no takedown scratch. The original finish rates about 98% and is free of any rust or pitting. The grips are in excellent condition as well with little wear and no cracks, chips or gouges. The mechanics appear to be in perfect working order and the bore is mirror bright with sharp rifling. This exceptional pistol comes with three original, late WWII General Shaver contract magazines as well as an unissued/original Boyt 45 marked holster w/ lanyard, original pistol belt, WWII double mag pouch (Boyle 1942), and original late war style Carlisle bandage in the original first aid pouch (Brede Inc. 1945). This pistol is serial number 2445758...the last 1911A1 produced by Remington Rand was 2465139...

title: For Sale/Trade:   Operation Shield Our Troops
postcontent:
Good afternoon,

My fiancée is a Mary Kay representative, and she is spear-heading a fund raiser to send our troops who are stationed in the Middle East sunscreen & lip balm sets. Operation Shield Our Troops is a small way of saying thank you to our military serving in the harsh desert climates of the Middle East. Will this totally nullify the sacrifice being made by them for all of us, in short, no, but if it can alleviate one aspect of the many conditions they deal with everyday, then what would it be to give that gift to them. Just to let them know that they are being thought of, appreciated, and possibly reinforce their mettle in the endeavor they have chosen to do, is a small price on our part to help them in any way we can. So please give generously, and know that for your donation you have made one of our troops time in service that much better. Every set that is donated, there will be a personalized card saying from whom the gift was donated by, so they know exactly who supported them in their time of sacrifice. If you could please circulate this, it would be greatly appreciated. She has set up a donation page; here is the link to the page, thank you.

http://www.gofundme.com/shieldourtroops 

Best wishes,
Charles L. MacLennan

title: For Sale:  Henry H004RR American Railroad Tribute Edition .22LR
postcontent:
BRAND NEW UNOPENED IN BOX.
$849.75
This .22 caliber Tribute Edition appropriately wears imagery that commemorates the 1869 event, displaying period-style scrollwork surrounding a 24K gold-plated Jupiter roaring into railroad legend, behind a gold bannered THE LAST RAIL IS LAID with a forward panel carrying a gold rendition of the Golden Spike next to another banner inscribed THE LAST SPIKE IS DRIVEN, on the right side of the polished nickel plated receiver cover.
The walnut stock bears the celebrated Promontory ceremonial image, laser-etched and hand filled, above a PROMONTORY, UTAH MAY 10, 1869 banner, and below the Morse Code letters DONE. On the fore-end, AMERICAN RAILROAD TRIBUTE is bordered by a stylized railroad track.
With one single word, telegraphed in Morse Code on May 10, 1869, history ushered in a new era, connecting both coasts via steel and wood that now spanned the continent for travel and commerce. The Union Pacific, driving hard from the East, and the Central Pacific from the West, met at Promontory Summit, in Utah Territory, after specially chosen Irish and Chinese workers took only 12 hours to lay the last 10 miles of track in time for the ceremony.
Positioning the Union Pacific’s No. 119 and the Central Pacific’s Jupiter locomotives facing each other one railroad tie’s length apart, photographer A.J Russell unlimbered his camera to document the unprecedented accomplishment, speeches were made, the famed Golden Spike was driven, champagne corks popped, and the telegrapher clicked the word “Done” on his key to notify the entire nation. The vast American railroad network now annually moves billions of tons of freight, and hundreds of thousands of people, all around our great country.
Henry Repeating Arms gratefully acknowledges the men and women who kept, and keep, the iron horse smoothly running with the American Railroad Tribute Edition Golden Boy. An outstanding American tribute to a vital American industry.

title: For Sale:  FEG SMC .380 ACP
postcontent:
For sale, FEG SMC .380 ACP.

A little background info on it -- this FEG is a Walther PPK clone made in Hungary imported by KBI in Harrisburg, PA. It's an interesting gun for several reasons. It is 4.1 inches so it could be imported under the Gun Control Act of 1968, and the left grip artificially widens it to 1.3 inches for the same reason, but if you switched out the grips it would be only 1.1 inches wide. It's a Walther PPK clone with an alloy frame so it's a few ounces lighter than the PPK.

This one was my daily concealed carry for a while because of that small size and light frame. It's got a beautiful blue finish on it too. Over time, however, the rear sights got loose in the dovetail, and the magazine got worn and caused feeding issues. It took too long to track down a replacement mag so I switched to a different weapon, and now this one is for sale.
